@node Usage
@chapter Getting Cairog

Cairog can be obtained in two ways depending on your use case.

@menu
* Direct Installation::   Install from source without a channel.
* Via Guix Channel::      Install and use cairog as a Guix dependency.
@end menu

@node Direct Installation
@section Direct Installation

If you have a local checkout of the cairog source, you can install it
directly into your Guix profile without any channel setup:

@example
guix package -f guix.scm
@end example

After installation the modules are available with no extra configuration:

@example
(use-modules (cairog))
@end example

@node Via Guix Channel
@section Via Guix Channel

The cairog Guix channel allows you to install cairog and declare it as
a dependency in your own Guix projects without a local checkout.

@subsection Adding the channel

Add the following to @file{~/.config/guix/channels.scm}:

@example
(cons* (channel
         (name 'cairog)
         (url "https://github.com/zictogo/cairog-channel"))
       %default-channels)
@end example

Then synchronise:

@example
guix pull
@end example

@subsection Installing cairog

@example
guix install cairog
@end example

@subsection Declaring cairog as a dependency

In your project's @file{guix.scm}:

@example
(use-modules (cairog packages)
             (guix packages)
             (guix build-system gnu)
             (gnu packages guile))

(package
  (name "my-project")
  ...
  (inputs (list cairog guile-3.0)))
@end example
